  "text": "CORRESPONDENCE 14 January 2025 By Emma Pierson1 Leah Pierson Harvard Medical School, Boston, Massachusetts, USA. Emma Pierson University of California, Berkeley, Berkeley, California, USA. Donald Trump’s incoming administration in the United States has signalled that it might significantly cut funding for research on infectious diseases, inequality and climate science, among other long-established areas (see Nature https://doi.org/nxdf (2024); Science https://doi.org/nxdg; 2024). If this happens, philanthropic funders should step in to help fill the gap. Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals Get Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription $29.99 / 30 days cancel any time Subscribe to this journal Receive 51 print issues and online access $199.00 per year only $3.90 per issue Rent or buy this article Prices vary by article type from$1.95 to$39.95 Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 637, 548 (2025) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-00112-4 Competing Interests The authors declare no competing interests. Related Articles What Trump’s election win could mean for AI, climate and health ‘We need to be ready for a new world’: scientists globally react to Trump election Will the Gates Foundation’s preprint-centric policy help open access? What steps to take when funding starts to run out See more letters to the editor Subjects Latest on:",
